  1. Make an animation
library(gganimate)
library(gifski)
data1<- newdata %>% group_by(moa,provider) %>% summarise(mean=mean(los))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'moa' (override with `.groups` argument)
data2<- data1 %>% group_by(moa) %>% mutate(rank=rank(-mean)) %>% ungroup()
data3<- data2 %>% filter(rank <=10)
library(knitr)


p1<- data3 %>% ggplot(aes(x=rank, y=mean,group=provider,fill=provider,label=provider)) + geom_col() +
  geom_text(aes(y=mean,label=provider),hjust=1.4)+
  coord_flip(clip="off",expand=FALSE)+
  scale_x_reverse()+
      labs(title = 'Month {closest_state}', x='', y='Length of Stay by provider', fill='')+
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 1, size = 22),
          axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
          axis.text.y  = element_blank()) + 
    transition_states(moa)+
    ease_aes("cubic-in-out")+ggsave("animate.png",dpi = 80)

III. Predictive Models

Continue with the data from part I. Use the follows as the target and input variables:

Target Variable: Create the target variable taking value of

  • low if the total charge of a patient (tot) is smaller than the median of the total charge, and

  • high otherwise.

Input Variables:

  • age,sex,raceethn,provider,moa,mod,admtype,campus, los
